TO BE, OR NOT TO BE.....<br>
           Sat Aug 2 20:25:22 US/Eastern 1997 <br><br>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
Thank you for the eloquent statement of you feelings. Like the old sci-fi movie &quot;When Words Collide&quot;, there is always chaos in any process, this site being no different than any other process in the conduct of human affairs.<br><br>
Diversity, openness, and honesty continue to be the tenets upon which the proprietors based this site, and it seems to continue along those lines. No one person owns it, no one person controlls it, and we seem all adult enough in the final analysis to understand the larger purpose at stake here: The freedom of expression, the freedom to be heard, the freedom to be understood, the freedom to feel human and unfettered by more local conventions of the microcosm in which we may find ourselves. &quot;All the world's a stage.&quot; This is a world stage. Anyone in the entire world may read all our words and comment. They do...and they do not, as they so<br>
desire.<br><br>
This site is also evolving through the participation of those whose wellspring, personality, ego, social orientation, bias, and communication ability are different that what has transpired in the past. It is evolving in ways that bring to light other Points of View, like Native American Traditions and the way of US Marines, for instance. Is this bad, some unleashed Hound of Hades, or a takeover by Mars, the God of War? I think not. I personally understand the Point of View of Native American Traditions, and welcome their impact upon this stage. Our &quot;modern&quot; society lacks the capacity to handle the spawn of its malfesance. Native      American philosophy gives many of us the illumination we need to continue to productively help ourselves and our self esteem. Carl Jung understood.<br><br>
The viewpoint of US Marines, though foreign to some, are very familiar to me. I must honor and respect their dedication and patriotism. Do NOT fail to remember it is the United States Government, and the American People, who *trained* these individuals to be Marines for some very good reasons. If you have a problem with their traditional views, the way they think, or the way they fight, complain to your Senator and Congressman.<br><br>
Now to a few specifics:<br><br>
&quot;...&quot;killing gooks&quot; is still a racist expression, and nothing to be proud of.&quot;<br><br>
It is not racist to kill the enemy, regardless of what you name him. I recall names flung on both sides of WWI and WWII and I do not see flagellation over that. Why is it an issue at all? <br><br>
&quot;Some of you older members of this thread seem to think you must embrace anyone because they too served. I think that is wrong.&quot;<br><br>
I do not see any meaning to this statement other than an accusation of taking sides by virtue of a uniform. Unfortunately, that is a misconception. Speaking for myself, there are things about which I disagree with everyone's viewpoint. I, however, do not let it get in the way of meeting people half way, interacting, and learning. In<br>
your context, the fact that I did not spit in the eye of someone vehemently disagreeing with you is &quot;taking sides&quot;. Bullshit.<br><br>
I have said enough to make the points I feel important.<br><br>
Doc, please continue in you dialog.<br><br>
Arthur
